<p>In May 2026, US semiconductor export controls entered a new phase of intensive lawmaking. Multiple tracks are converging simultaneously: the MATCH Act advancing through the House Foreign Affairs Committee, Micron lobbying to restrict chip equipment sales to Chinese rivals (Reuters, May 8 2026), and the Commerce Department exploring new restrictions on Chinese AI chip makers.</p>

<p>These moves together sketch the key semiconductor geopolitics trend of 2026: <strong>export controls are shifting from "targeted restrictions" to "systematic decoupling."</strong></p>

<h2>The MATCH Act: Filling the Loopholes</h2>
<p>Critics identified three major gaps in existing US chip export controls: gray market channels through third countries (Malaysia, Vietnam, Mexico); uncontrolled consumer-grade chips being bulk-purchased by Chinese AI companies; and uneven enforcement by allies like ASML and Tokyo Electron.</p>
<p>The MATCH Act targets these gaps: expanded end-use review, third-party transshipment controls, and new export license requirements for AI accelerator chips.</p>

<h2>Micron's Campaign: Weaponizing Commercial Competition</h2>
<p>Reuters' exclusive reveals that Micron is pushing to restrict chip equipment sales to Chinese competitors like ChangXin Memory and Yangtze Memory. CSIS notes this marks a dangerous trend: semiconductor export controls are evolving from "national security tools" to "industrial policy weapons." When commercial competition and national security blur, export controls lose strategic precision.</p>

<h2>Chain Effects</h2>
<p><strong>On China</strong>: accelerated "de-Americanized" computing autonomy. CSIS notes that each restricted link — from EDA tools to photoresist to advanced packaging — is spawning domestic alternatives, though "full-stack autonomy" requires 5-10 years and hundreds of billions in investment.</p>
<p><strong>On global supply chains</strong>: formation of "two ecosystems" — the US-controlled EUV ecosystem vs. China's emerging alternative. This means higher chip costs and increased design complexity worldwide.</p>
<p><strong>On US allies</strong>: caught in the middle. ASML and Tokyo Electron face the dilemma of "losing the China market" vs. "complying with US rules."</p>

<h2>Implications for Chinese Companies</h2>
<p>Computing cost increases are a certainty; backup strategies are no longer optional but mandatory; regulatory compliance capability becomes competitive advantage; autonomous computing is a structural long-term investment, not a short-term refuge.</p>

